# Need of Encapsulation
    Let’s think you're building a student app in Java. Each student has details like name, marks, and roll number.
    What if someone from outside the class changes a student’s marks and sets them to -50? Or changes the roll number to "ABC123"?
    That would break your program.

    When other parts of your code can directly change data, it's risky. Anyone can make a mistake, even by accident.
    You need a way to protect your data and control how it is used. This is why we use encapsulation.

    Encapsulation helps you keep your data safe. It also helps you decide who can read or change the values inside your class.

Q1. What Exactly Is Encapsulation?
Standard Definition:
    Encapsulation is the process of putting data (variables) and methods (functions) together inside one class, and hiding the internal details from other classes.

Simple Explanation:
    Think of your phone. You can use the apps, press buttons, and make calls. But you cannot touch the inside parts of the phone —
    the hardware and wiring are hidden. You only use what is shown on the screen.

    Encapsulation in Java works the same way. You hide the inside data of a class and only show what’s needed through public methods.

Q2. Why Is Encapsulation So Important? 🎯
    Encapsulation is important because it helps you:
        1. Protect your data from being changed wrongly
        2. Control how your data is accessed or updated
        3. Hide unnecessary internal details from outside classes
        4. Keep your code clean and safe
        5. Make future changes easier — because other parts of your code don’t depend on internal details

    Encapsulation gives you full control over your class and how it’s used.

# Common Interview Questions:

    Q1. What is encapsulation in Java?
    Answer:
        Encapsulation is the concept of wrapping data (variables) and code (methods) into a single unit and hiding the
        internal details from outside access. It is achieved by making variables private and providing public methods to access and modify them.

    Q2. How do you achieve encapsulation in Java?
    Answer:
        By declaring the class variables as private and creating public getter and setter methods to access and update those variables.

    Q3. What is the main purpose of encapsulation?
    Answer:
        The main purpose of encapsulation is to protect data from unwanted access or modification.
        It allows the class to control what values are allowed and how the data is used.

    Q4. Can you explain encapsulation with a real-life example?
    Answer:
        Yes. An ATM machine is a good example. You can only access your account through specific options (buttons), and you cannot directly modify your bank balance.
        The machine controls how your request is handled. This is similar to encapsulation, where the class controls access to its data.

# Summary

    Writing Java code without encapsulation may look simple in small programs, but it leads to big problems in real-world applications. When your class data is public:
    1. Anyone can change it, even with wrong values
    2. There are no checks, no rules, and no security
    3. Your code becomes harder to manage and easier to break
    4. You cannot track or control how your data is being used

    Encapsulation solves all of these issues by hiding data and giving safe, controlled access through methods.
    It helps you build programs that are clean, secure, and professional.

# Common Interview Questions:

    Q1. What happens if you don't use encapsulation in Java?
    Answer: If you don’t use encapsulation, your class variables can be accessed and changed from anywhere.
            This can lead to wrong or harmful values being added to your objects, and your program can easily break.

    Q2. Why is using public variables directly considered bad practice?
    Answer: Public variables give no control over the values being set. Anyone can enter invalid data (like a negative balance),
            and the class cannot protect itself from incorrect use.

    Q3. How does encapsulation fix the problems in the BankAccount example?
    Answer: Encapsulation allows you to hide the data using private variables and control access using getter and setter methods.
            This helps validate values before updating them, making the class safer and more secure.

    Q4. Can a Java class work without encapsulation?
    Answer: Yes, technically it will work, but it’s not safe. In professional or real-world applications,
            it’s strongly recommended to use encapsulation to protect your data and maintain control over your class.

    Q5. Is encapsulation only about hiding variables?
    Answer: No, encapsulation is also about controlling how data is accessed and changed. It’s about protecting your class from incorrect use and improving maintainability.